# Verilog Digital Design – 8-bit Adder

This repository contains two implementations of an 8-bit adder written in Verilog.

The goal of this project is to demonstrate the difference between behavioral RTL design and structural design, while also verifying that both implementations produce identical results through simulation.

------------------------------------------------------------

IMPLEMENTATIONS

Behavioral Adder

The behavioral implementation uses Verilog arithmetic operators to describe the adder functionality.

Example:

assign {cout,sum} = a + b + cin;

In this approach, the synthesizer infers the required hardware automatically based on the RTL description.

This method is commonly used in RTL design because it produces clean and concise code while allowing synthesis tools to optimize the hardware implementation.

------------------------------------------------------------

Structural Adder

The structural implementation explicitly builds the adder using bit-level logic equations.

Each bit of the adder is implemented using the full-adder equations:

Sum = A XOR B XOR Cin

Cout = (A AND B) OR ((A XOR B) AND Cin)

By chaining multiple full adders together, the design forms a ripple carry adder.

This approach demonstrates how arithmetic circuits can be constructed directly from basic logic operations.

------------------------------------------------------------

Testbench

The testbench instantiates both implementations:

- behave_addr
- struct_addr

The testbench applies multiple input combinations and compares the outputs of both implementations to verify that they behave identically.

The simulation also demonstrates signed overflow detection for the adder.

